            "@type": "PropertyValue",
            "name": "backstory",
            "value": "Paolo Reyes is San Francisco born and bred, a product of the fog-laced avenues of Daly City. The youngest of three children born to Filipino immigrants, his father drove a Muni bus for thirty years and his mother cleaned rooms at a hotel near Union Square. Their lives were a testament to tireless work, and college was a luxury they couldn't afford to promise. Paolo, never a strong student, felt the quiet pressure to contribute as soon as he graduated from high school.\n\nHe drifted through his early twenties, working in kitchens and stocking shelves, feeling untethered from the city that was rapidly changing around him. The turning point came when his grandmother, his *lola*, suffered a debilitating stroke. Paolo became one of her primary caregivers, learning the rhythms of patience, compassion, and physical assistance. The experience of helping her navigate her new limitations ignited an unexpected calling. He enrolled in a certification program and became a Certified Nursing Assistant.\n\nFor the last twelve years, Paolo has worked as a CNA at a public school serving students with severe developmental and physical disabilities. His daily 4.5-mile commute on the 29-Sunset bus from his Outer Richmond apartment to the Bayview is his time to decompress, listening to old-school hip-hop on his headphones. His work is physically demanding and emotionally draining, but the small victories\u2014a non-verbal student making eye contact, a child mastering the use of a fork\u2014provide a profound sense of purpose that his earlier jobs lacked.\n\nPaolo\u2019s life is built on routine and connection. He lives in a small, rent-controlled one-bedroom apartment he\u2019s had for a decade. His social life revolves around Sunday dinners at his parents' house and a weekly pickup basketball game with his cousins at a park in the Excelsior. He is part of San Francisco\u2019s unseen engine: the essential workers who keep the city running while its tech fortunes ebb and flow. His dream isn't to get rich, but to one day pursue a Licensed Vocational Nurse (LVN) degree. Until then, he finds his wealth in the quiet dignity of his work and the deep, unassuming love for the city that has always been his only home."
        },
        {
            "@type": "PropertyValue",
            "name": "reveries",
            "value": "1.\nHe remembers the scent of ginger and chicken in his lola\u2019s room, a few months after the stroke. He was trying to feed her arroz caldo, but she kept turning away in frustration. Defeated, he put the spoon down. Then, her small, trembling hand found his wrist and squeezed. It wasn't about the food; it was about his presence. In that silent moment of connection, a path forward lit up, one built not on ambition, but on simple, steady compassion. He enrolled in his CNA program the next week.\n\n2.\nIt was his first year working at the school. He\u2019d spent months with Leo, a boy locked in his own world, who never made eye contact. One rainy Tuesday, while trying to get him to stack blocks, Paolo felt a gaze on him. He looked up, and Leo was staring right at him. Leo then slowly lifted a small hand and pointed to the red block. The classroom noise faded. For Paolo, that tiny intentional gesture was an earthquake, a validation so profound it anchored him to his purpose forever.\n\n3.\nHe was on the 29-Sunset, head nodding to A Tribe Called Quest, watching the fog snake down the avenues. A sleek, black tech shuttle glided past. For a second, he felt like a ghost in his own city. Then he thought of his dad driving his Muni route for thirty years, the thousands of faces he knew, the lives he carried. The rumble of Paolo's bus felt more real, more vital. He wasn't on the outside looking in; he was part of the city's steady, rhythmic heartbeat.\n\n4.\nThe court at the Excelsior playground was cracked, the net frayed. Last Sunday, he\u2019d driven the lane, a clumsy move, and tossed up a wild layup that somehow dropped in. The game stopped as his cousins howled with laughter and slapped his back. In their easy, familiar teasing, Paolo felt a kind of wealth no salary could buy. This was his San Francisco\u2014not the skyline, but the sound of family laughter echoing on a worn-out court, a connection that had never changed.\n\n5.\nOne night last year, after a long shift, he stood in his quiet living room in the Outer Richmond. The fog was thick against the window, muffling the city. His gaze fell on his CNA certificate, tacked to the wall. He thought of the kids, of his parents' tireless work, of the decade he\u2019d spent in that very room. There was no great fortune here, no grand story. Just the quiet dignity of a life built on routine and care. He felt a profound sense of peace, realizing he wasn't adrift at all."
